the summer of 1876. It was originally transmitted by Jim Ka-Nipitehtew's father directly to him and the authors comment on this remarkable chain of transmission. The book contains a Cree-English and an English-Cree Glossary. This is an important resource for Cree linguistics as well as those interested in understanding the Cree perspective of Treaty 6.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Multiple languages.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCree IndiansxHistory. 0aCree IndiansxReligion. 0aCree languagevDictionariesxEnglish. 0aCree languagevDictionaries. 0aCree languagevTexts. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAhenakew, Freda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKâ-Nîpitêhtêw, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolfart, H.C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWolfart, H.C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755371440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553714423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553714/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles